essence, a supraventricular rhythm (Table 5). The term ‘narrow QRS tachycardia’ indicates those with a QRS duration <_120 ms. A wide QRS tachycardia refers to one with a QRS duration >120 ms (Table 6). In clinical practice, SVT may present as narrow or wide QRS tachycardias, most of which, although not invariably, manifest as regular rhythms. These Guidelines do not cover AF, which is the subject of separate clinical Guidelines4 and various consensus documents.5À7

