Acute therapy
Haemodynamically unstable patients Synchronized DC cardioversion is recommended for haemodynamically unstable patients.86À88
Haemodynamically stable patients Vagal manoeuvres, preferably in the supine position with leg elevation, are recommended.41,89À91
In orthodromic AVRT, adenosine (6À18 mg i.v. bolus) is recommended if vagal manoeuvres fail and the tachycardia is orthodromic.92À94 In orthodromic AVRT, i.v. verapamil or diltiazem should be considered if vagal manoeuvres and adenosine fail.92,94À98
In orthodromic AVRT, i.v. beta-blockers (esmolol or metoprolol) should be considered in the absence of decompensated HF, if vagal manoeuvres and adenosine fail.97,99,100
In antidromic AVRT, i.v. ibutilide or procainamide or i.v. ﬂecainide or profanenone or synchronized DC cardioversion should be considered if vagal manoeuvres and adenosine fail.421,422,429,437 In antidromic AVRT, i.v. amiodarone may be considered in refractory cases.423À425,435 Synchronized DC cardioversion is recommended when drug therapy fails to convert or control the tachycardia.87,88
Chronic therapy Catheter ablation of AP(s) is recommended in patients with symptomatic, recurrent AVRT.391À393,438À441
Beta-blockers or non-dihydropyridine calcium-channel blockers (verapamil or diltiazem in the absence of HFrEF) should be considered if no signs of pre-excitation are present on resting ECG, if ablation is not desirable or feasible.340,341,442,443
Propafenone or ﬂecainide may be considered in patients with AVRT and without ischaemic or structural heart disease, if ablation is not desirable or feasible.429,444,445
Digoxin, beta-blockers, diltiazem, verapamil, and amiodarone are not recommended and are potentially harmful in patients with pre-excited AF.427,428,432À434,446

